@model ContactFormModel

@*
    Copy here is placeholder and Scott's to rewrite. Structure follows a standard
    conversion contact page: one clear ask, a short form, reassurance right at the button.
*@

<section class="section--lede">
    <div class="container container--form">
        <p class="topper">Contact</p>
        <h1 class="header">Schedule a consultation</h1>
        <p class="text lede__text">
            Tell me what you're working with and what you need. nopCommerce, an existing .NET
            application, or a new site. Call or email for pricing and estimates, or send a few
            lines below and I'll get back to you.
        </p>

        @* Visible text AND links, so a phone taps to call on mobile and the address opens the
           mail client. tel: is in E.164 (no spaces/punctuation) so every dialer parses it. *@
        <ul class="contact-methods">
            <li>
                <span class="contact-methods__label">Call</span>
                <a href="tel:+17205742380">(720) 574-2380</a>
            </li>
            <li>
                <span class="contact-methods__label">Email</span>
                <a href="mailto:scott@scottneidig.com">scott@scottneidig.com</a>
            </li>
        </ul>

        @*
            Authority line, not a price line. "Competitive with agencies" is a value claim
            (ex-agency work, direct, no agency overhead), backed by Scott having worked at
            agencies and knowing what they bill. Deliberately NOT "affordable" — that reads as
            junior and undercuts the org-tier positioning. Placeholder wording for Scott.
        *@
        <p class="contact-authority">
            I've done this work inside agencies, where it bills at a premium. Direct, my rates
            are competitive with theirs, without the overhead in between.
        </p>

        <form method="post" class="form form--contact">
            <div asp-validation-summary="ModelOnly" class="form__errors" role="alert"></div>

            <div class="form__field">
                <label asp-for="Name"></label>
                <input asp-for="Name" autocomplete="name" />
                <span asp-validation-for="Name" class="form__error"></span>
            </div>

            <div class="form__field">
                <label asp-for="Email"></label>
                <input asp-for="Email" type="email" autocomplete="email" />
                <span asp-validation-for="Email" class="form__error"></span>
            </div>

            <div class="form__field">
                <label asp-for="Message"></label>
                <textarea asp-for="Message" rows="6"></textarea>
                <span asp-validation-for="Message" class="form__error"></span>
            </div>

            @*
                Honeypot. Hidden from people and from the accessibility tree, so no human or
                screen reader ever fills it; a bot that does gets silently dropped. aria-hidden
                and tabindex keep it out of keyboard and AT flow.
            *@
            <div class="hp" aria-hidden="true">
                <label asp-for="Website">Website</label>
                <input asp-for="Website" tabindex="-1" autocomplete="off" />
            </div>

            <div class="form__actions">
                <button class="button" type="submit">Send message</button>
            </div>

            <p class="form__reassure">
                Goes straight to me, and a real person reads it. I usually reply within a
                business day.
            </p>
        </form>
    </div>
</section>
